0=Strong

2=Weak

Definition: The text of the remarks section of a message.

JMCDM Attribute Name: GEOPHYSICAL-POINT-OBSERVATION-MESSAGE remark text and RUNWAY-CONDITION remarks text
DDDS Counter:  42026 

                 JMCDM Attribute Name: WEATHER-HAZARD-ADVISORY remarks text

Measured in Milliseconds.

rollderived by: xsd:float      
documentation
The ATHWARTSHIPS angular rotation of the sonar platform's center of gravity  at the time of the detection.  Measured in Angular-Degrees.
yawderived by: xsd:float      
documentation
The angular rotation about the vertical axis of the sonar platform's center of gravity at the time of the detection.  Meaured in Angular-Degrees.

documentation
The angle, measured from true North, of the contact from the sonar. Measured in Angular-Degrees.
contactRangederived by: xsd:float

The horizontal distance dimension of the contact from the sonar. Measured in Meters.

attribute baseReferenceTime
type restriction of IntegerDateTime_Type
facets
minInclusive 00010101000000
maxInclusive 99991231235959
annotation
documentation
                
Definition: The calendar date and time of the geophysical data contained in a GEOPHYSICAL-ANALYSIS-FORECAST.
Units of Measure:  N/A

JMCDM Attribute Name: GEOPHYSICAL-ANALYSIS-FORECAST base reference calendar date-time
DDDS Counter: 47400
Functional Area Id:  3
STDZ Status Code:  A
Security Category:  UNCLASSIFIED
Authority Reference Text:  World Meteorological Organization Manual On Codes, International Codes (WMO 306).
Domain Definition:  A general domain comprised of a mandatory 14-character field. The mandatory 14-character field consists of the format YYYYMMDDHHMMSS where: YYYY represents a calendar year and can contain any positive integer value; MM represents the ordinal number of a calendar month within the calendar year and is restricted to the values 01-12; DD represents the ordinal number of a day within the calendar month and is restricted to the values 01-31; HH represents an ordinal hour within the day and is restricted to the values 00-23; MM represents an ordinal minute within the hour and is restricted to the values 00-59; SS represents an ordinal second within the minute and is restricted to the values 00-59.
Version: 2
Comment Text:  The base time (universal time coordinated) for an analysis model is the valid time of the analysis.  The base time(universal time coordinated) for a forecast model is the reference time from which all forecasts are based.

attribute ordinateOrganizationId
type OrganizationIdentifier_Type
facets
length 4
annotation
documentation

Definition: The identifier that represents an administrative structure with a mission.
Units of Measure:
JMCDM Attribute Name: ORGANIZATION identifier
DDDS Counter 7875
Functional Area Id:  77
STDZ Status Code:  A
Security Category:  UNCLASSIFIED
Authority Reference Text:  U.S. CODE TITLE 10, CHAPTER 301
Domain Definition:  A GENERAL DOMAIN CONSISTING OF FOUR BYTES UNSIGNEDINTEGER (32 BITS).  THIS IS APPROXIMATELY 4.3 BILLION(**32) ITERATION.                
Version: 2
Comment Text:  Organization identifier (org-id) is a four-byte (32 bits)unsigned integer.  It is used as a surrogate key (no businessmeaning).  A 32-bit unsigned integer has the capability to uniquely enumerate more than 4.3 billion organizations(actually, 2**32), provided that all the possible numbers are used.  Integer values are assigned first-come, first-served,with no waste.  This has three obvious advantages:  (1) it is very general; (2) it provides a very terse manner in which to identify organizations, and (3) it allows the computers to do simple integer operations that are very fast.  There can be organization entity.  A basic assumption is that operators will not be accessing databases directly but will use application programs that in turn access databases.  Thus,operators will be insulated from details like "surrogate keys."  Administration of this approach is done with a set of seamless org-id servers.  The org-id servers are developed and maintained by the DoD CIO.  When an authorized user wants to create a new organization, an org-id must be obtained.  A request is sent to one of several org-id servers.  The requestor must return to the server the status, active or inactive, of the org-id requested.  The purpose of an org-id server is to ensure that org-ids are unique.  The actual organization information is located in "organization servers" maintained by the individual services or agencies.
source <xsd:attribute name="ordinateOrganizationId" type="OrganizationIdentifier_Type">
  <xsd:annotation>
    <xsd:documentation>
Definition: The identifier that represents an administrative structure with a mission.
Units of Measure:
JMCDM Attribute Name: ORGANIZATION identifier
DDDS Counter 7875
Functional Area Id:  77
STDZ Status Code:  A
Security Category:  UNCLASSIFIED
Authority Reference Text:  U.S. CODE TITLE 10, CHAPTER 301
Domain Definition:  A GENERAL DOMAIN CONSISTING OF FOUR BYTES UNSIGNEDINTEGER (32 BITS).  THIS IS APPROXIMATELY 4.3 BILLION(**32) ITERATION.                
Version: 2
Comment Text:  Organization identifier (org-id) is a four-byte (32 bits)unsigned integer.  It is used as a surrogate key (no businessmeaning).  A 32-bit unsigned integer has the capability to uniquely enumerate more than 4.3 billion organizations(actually, 2**32), provided that all the possible numbers are used.  Integer values are assigned first-come, first-served,with no waste.  This has three obvious advantages:  (1) it is very general; (2) it provides a very terse manner in which to identify organizations, and (3) it allows the computers to do simple integer operations that are very fast.  There can be organization entity.  A basic assumption is that operators will not be accessing databases directly but will use application programs that in turn access databases.  Thus,operators will be insulated from details like "surrogate keys."  Administration of this approach is done with a set of seamless org-id servers.  The org-id servers are developed and maintained by the DoD CIO.  When an authorized user wants to create a new organization, an org-id must be obtained.  A request is sent to one of several org-id servers.  The requestor must return to the server the status, active or inactive, of the org-id requested.  The purpose of an org-id server is to ensure that org-ids are unique.  The actual organization information is located in "organization servers" maintained by the individual services or agencies.
</xsd:documentation>
  </xsd:annotation>
</xsd:attribute>

attribute personId
type restriction of xsd:string
facets
maxLength 16
annotation
documentation

Definition: The identifier that represents a PERSON.
Units of Measure:

JMCDM Attribute Name: PERSON Identifier
DDDS Counter: 11185  
Functional Area Id: 81  
STDZ Status Code: A  
Security Category: UNCLASSIFIED  
Authority Reference Text: U. S. CODE TITLE 10, CHAPTER 36  
Domain Definition: A general domain comprised of the characters in the ASCII graphic character set.  
Version: 2  
Comment Text: Person identifier is constructed as follows. If the person has a social security number, use the concatenation  of the letter "s" and the social security number. Otherwise use "r" plus the resident alien identification card  number. Otherwise, "t" plus the country code plus the foreign country tax payer identification number, or "i" plus the  country code plus the foreign country identification number, or "p" plus the country code plus the foreign passport  number should be used as required by standing agreements with the local country (the order listed is preferred). For  special cases such as medical emergency, use "z" plus a pseudo-social security number. In the event that any of the above identifiers is determined to have been applied to more than one individual, a single-digit counter will be appended  to each duplicated string.

STDZ Status Code:  A
Security Category:  UNCLASSIFIED
Authority Reference Text:  U.S. CODE TITLE 10, CHAPTER 31
Domain Definition: A GENERAL DOMAIN COMPRISED OF THE CHARACTERS IN THE ASCII GRAPHIC CHARACTER SET.                 
Version: 1
Comment Text: Person full legal name is contructed by concatenating the following sequence of atomic data elements:1.  person-surname text, followed by one blank space;2.  person-forename text, followed by one blank space;3.  person-middle-name text, followed by one blank space;4.  person-cadency-name text.each respective atomic element will be associated with a person-name-usage record in which the person-name-usage code is set to the value l - legal name.  Note:  Specific ordering of the standard data element components is based on DOD 5000.12-m 2.3.5.3, rules for formation of name, individual.

attribute subordinateOrganizationId
type OrganizationIdentifier_Type
facets
length 4
annotation
documentation

Definition: The identifier that represents an administrative structure with a mission.
Units of Measure:
JMCDM Attribute Name: ORGANIZATION identifier
DDDS Counter 7875
Functional Area Id:  77
STDZ Status Code:  A
Security Category:  UNCLASSIFIED
Authority Reference Text:  U.S. CODE TITLE 10, CHAPTER 301
Domain Definition:  A GENERAL DOMAIN CONSISTING OF FOUR BYTES UNSIGNEDINTEGER (32 BITS).  THIS IS APPROXIMATELY 4.3 BILLION(**32) ITERATION.                
Version: 2
Comment Text:  Organization identifier (org-id) is a four-byte (32 bits)unsigned integer.  It is used as a surrogate key (no business meaning).  A 32-bit unsigned integer has the capability to uniquely enumerate more than 4.3 billion organizations(actually, 2**32), provided that all the possible numbers are used.  Integer values are assigned first-come, first-served,with no waste.  This has three obvious advantages:  (1) it is very general; (2) it provides a very terse manner in which toidentify organizations, and (3) it allows the computers to dosimple integer operations that are very fast.  There can be organization entity.  A basic assumption is that operators will not be accessing databases directly but will use application programs that in turn access databases.  Thus,operators will be insulated from details like "surrogate keys."  Administration of this approach is done with a set of seamless org-id servers.  The org-id servers are developed and maintained by the DoD CIO.  When an authorized user wants to create a new organization, an org-id must be obtained.  A request is sent to one of several org-id servers.  The requestor must return to the server the status, active or inactive, of the org-id requested.  The purpose of an org-id server is to ensure that org-ids are unique.  The actual organization information is located in "organization servers" maintained by the individual services or agencies.

JMCDM Attribute Name: CATALOG-ITEM creating organization identifier

simpleType DecimalDateTime_Type
type restriction of xsd:decimal
facets
minInclusive 00010101000000.000000
maxInclusive 99991231235959.999999
fractionDigits 6
annotation
documentation

Definition: The calendar date and time represented as a number containing fractional digits.
Domain Definition:   A general domain comprised of a mandatory 14-character field and an optional 3-character field. The mandatory 14-character field consists of the format YYYYMMDDHHMMSS where: YYYY represents a calendar year and can contain any positive integer value; MM represents the ordinal number of a calendar month within the calendar year and is restricted to the values 01-12; DD represents the ordinal number of a day within the calendar month and is restricted to the values 01-31; HH represents an ordinal hour within the day and is restricted to the values 00-23; MM represents an ordinal minute within the hour and is restricted to the values 00-59; SS represents an ordinal second within the minute and is restricted to the values 00-59.  The optional 3-character field allows the data element creator to specify the level of precision to be used when capturing seconds to the tenths or hundredths of a second, and consists of a decimal point followed by one character with a value, 0-9, for the capture of tenths of seconds, or two characters with the value, 00-99,when capturing hundredths of a second.

simpleType OrganizationIdentifier_Type
type restriction of xsd:base64Binary
facets
length 4
annotation
documentation

Definition: The identifier that represents an administrative structure with a mission.
JMCDM Attribute Name: ORGANIZATION identifier
DDDS Counter:  7875
Comment Text:  Organization identifier (org-id) is a four-byte (32 bits)unsigned integer.  It is used as a surrogate key (no business meaning).  A 32-bit unsigned integer has the capability to uniquely enumerate more than 4.3 billion organizations(actually, 2**32), provided that all the possible numbers are used.  Integer values are assigned first-come, first-served,with no waste.  This has three obvious advantages:  (1) it is very general; (2) it provides a very terse manner in which to identify organizations, and (3) it allows the computers to do simple integer operations that are very fast.  There can be organization entity.  A basic assumption is that operators will not be accessing databases directly but will use application programs that in turn access databases.  Thus,operators will be insulated from details like "surrogate keys."  Administration of this approach is done with a set of seamless org-id servers.  The org-id servers are developed and maintained by the DoD CIO.  When an authorized user wants to create a new organization, an org-id must be obtained.  A request is sent to one of several org-id servers.  The requestor must return to the server the status, active or inactive, of the org-id requested.  The purpose of an org-id server is to ensure that org-ids are unique.  The actual organization information is located in "organization servers" maintained by the individual services or agencies.
source <xsd:simpleType name="OrganizationIdentifier_Type">
  <xsd:annotation>
    <xsd:documentation>
